All member states of the European Union have agreed to protect the deposits of individual savers. For this reason, and in accordance with EU specifications, national deposit guarantee schemes have been put in place to secure the savings deposits of private customers.
What about banks outside of the Euro area?
Member states outside the Euro area ensure that the amounts of national currencies effectively paid to depositors are equivalent to those set out in the {{link}}
When does it go into effect?

In the event of a financial crisis and in case a bank cannot repay their customers’ deposits (or is unable to repay them on time), the national deposit guarantee scheme steps in and provides repayment. Amounts of up to €100.000 per bank are thereby protected for each customer.

N26 Savings gives you easy access to the best fixed term savings plans of banks across Europe. In a fixed term savings plan, you lock a specific amount of money for a specific duration into a bank account.

In return for the fixed amount and duration, banks are willing to pay significantly higher interest compared to normal savings accounts. However, this also means that you cannot withdraw your money from this account until the term matures. At the end of the term, the accumulated interest is paid out to you together with your initial investment amount.

The partner bank is the actual bank behind the fixed term savings offer. These are the ones that will pay out the pre-defined interest to you. To provide their offerings on our platform they had to go through a check undertaken by WeltSparen (Raisin GmbH). We have banks from several European countries on our platform.

MHB Bank is the partner bank of WeltSparen that runs its banking infrastructure. Their role is to make sure the money is transferred to the right partner bank into the right account. When you open a savings plan with N26 Savings, your money will first be transferred to an account at MHB Bank and then from MHB Bank to your new savings account at your partner bank.

To give you the best fixed term savings products, we teamed up with WeltSparen (Raisin GmbH). They have built a network of European product banks with attractive saving offerings and integrated them into one platform. More than 75.000 customers have already invested more than €3 billion through this network. N26 accesses this platform and allows you to take advantage of its offerings with a few taps. WeltSparen makes sure that each party in the partner network receives the required info and documents and that the money flows into the right directions.
The tax identification number (TIN) is used to register relevant financial activities for every individual. Despite its name, it can contain letters, and is different lengths in different countries.
Where to find your Tax ID?
You can find your tax identification number (TIN) on tax reports or pay slips. If you can’t find your tax ID it can also be requested from your national tax authority.
The request for a tax identification number (TIN) is a regulatory requirement of the European Union (EU) under the EU Savings Directive.
For our fixed savings product, we teamed up with WeltSparen (Raisin GmbH), the #1 deposit marketplace in Europe. With its {{partner}} we can give you access to the best saving offers.

WeltSparen provides the network of partner banks and the infrastructure required to offer savings deposits on the N26 platform. This allows us to make the most competitive fixed term deposits of Europe accessible with the tap of a finger.
What does WeltSparen do for N26?

"MHB-Bank AG is WeltSparen's servicing bank that provides their banking infrastructure. Established in 1973 and based in Frankfurt am Main, MHB-Bank has a German banking license and is regulated by the German financial supervisory authority (Bundesanstalt für Finanzdienstleistungsaufsicht - BaFin)."

WeltSparen is a marketplace that offers competitive interest rates for savings deposits of partner banks. Established in 2013 and based in Berlin, WeltSparen has won more than 27 awards including \"best German term deposit marketplace\" in 2014 and 2015, as voted on by the independent German rating portal Bankingcheck. Over 75.000 customers have already opened term deposits with WeltSparen at a total volume of more than €3 billion. Weltsparen is a service by Raisin GmbH.

"The withholding tax is a tax deducted from payment or income. It's directly paid by the sender of the money. It's charged by some countries on interest or dividends. Withholding taxes from a salary is the most common case."
Please note that the withholding tax amount will depend on your personal and individual asset positions. We advise you to seek individual tax advice.
How can I claim a tax exemption order?

"The tax on capital gains only applies to capital gains above the exempt amount of €801 for singles - or €1.620 combined for married partners. To claim a tax exemption order because your interest payments fall in the exempt amount, please visit our document center in the N26 Support Center, fill out the tax exemption form that belongs to the bank of your choice and submit the form to us per email. We'll forward it to your partner bank.
If you are not liable to pay the church tax, you will also find a form for an exemption order for this tax in our document center in the N26 Support Center."
Does this tax apply to me? How much is it?

"First Save €uro and Inbank do not withhold taxes. The full amount of interest earnings is paid out to you. It's your responsibility to declare your interest income in your tax returns.
For customers tax-liable in Germany, Grenke Bank and Greensill Bank are obliged by German law to withhold the capital gains, solidarity and {{churchtax}}. The bank automatically deducts all applicable taxes from your investment if you are a tax resident of Germany. This means that the interest paid out to you always reflects the net amount after taxes. The withholding tax is roughly up to 28% on your interest earned (may be up to 2% lower in individual cases). You can, however, file a tax exemption form for the tax on capital gains as well as the church tax."
